<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Former Daf workers win Pounds 10m award: Tribunal condemns
receivers for ignoring legal obligations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS made redundant after the financial collapse of Leyland Daf, the UK
subsidiary of the failed Dutch truck maker, won compensation technically
worth about Pounds 10m yesterday.
Unions claimed a 'famous victory' after an industrial tribunal censured
receivers of the former truck company for ignoring employment laws.
The tribunal ruled that 2,400 workers in Leyland in Lancashire, Birmingham
and Glasgow were made redundant unlawfully because neither their employers
nor the receivers who took over last February gave them the statutory 90
days' notice.
The tribunal strongly criticised the receivers Mr Murdoch McKillop and Mr
John Talbot of Arthur Andersen. It said: 'It is very surprising that the
administrative receivers of eminence involved in this case should fail to
meet their statutory obligations so repeatedly and so lamentably as they
have done here.'
The receivers argued yesterday that when they moved in they were fighting to
keep the business alive, and there had been no alternative but to issue
redundancy notices.
Mr McKillop said: 'As receivers we had to use what limited funds that were
available to save what was left of the company. The alternative was complete
closure.'
The Leyland Daf case mirrors a successful claim by 700 former workers of the
Swan Hunter shipyard on Tyneside who were awarded Pounds 1.5m compensation
in September.
Although yesterday's award was worth Pounds 10m, the unions will have to
seek payment from the Department of Employment redundancy scheme, as they
are unable to lodge a claim with the company. The government scheme would
give them a potential maximum award of nearly Pounds 4m and, because
compensation is likely to be offset by pay in lieu of notice, the final
payment could be even lower.
Mr John Allen, AEEU engineering union chief negotiator at Leyland Daf, said:
'While no amount of money can compensate those who were unceremoniously
sacked, the union has established an important principle. Companies and
receivers will in future have to obey the law or face the consequences. Just
because a company is facing financial difficulty they clearly have no right
to behave in an arbitrary and cavalier manner and expect to get away with
it.'
Mr Michael Short, the union lawyer, said the tribunal made it clear there
was no excuse for the 'brutal and unfair' manner in which the receivers
dismissed workers. He added: 'Unfortunately it seems the company has no
money to pay the awards. We are now looking to recover the money from the
government.'
</TEXT>
