<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Revenue criticises DTI proposals on creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Inland Revenue yesterday criticised Department of Trade and Industry
proposals that threaten its preferential status as a creditor to companies
in financial difficulties.
It argued that its priority ranking above other creditors was 'necessary',
and wants it to be maintained in any changes to insolvency legislation.
The comments were in response to a DTI consultative document issued on
Tuesday which called for an overhaul of existing procedures for company
voluntary arrangements (CVAs) and administration orders. The document said
some countries were eliminating or reducing the number of preferential tax
creditors, and suggested that 'Crown preference' for pay-as-you-earn, value
added tax and other measures could be removed.
Banks yesterday maintained their tentative support for the proposals, which
would require them to lose some of their rights as priority creditors by
abiding by CVAs and giving a company seven days' notice before appointing
receivers.
One banker said he supported the principle of trying to rescue more
companies. But he questioned how far the proposals would succeed. 'So many
of the companies we see are bust by the time they suggest a CVA,' he said.
</TEXT>
