<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Investors 'misled about forecasts'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FORMER chairman of Harland Simon, the electronics company, had no
knowledge that the company's profit forecasts would be revised downwards
soon after he allegedly spoke to two institutional investors about its
likely results, he told Aylesbury Crown Court yesterday.
Mr Roy Ashman is alleged, at a meeting last February, to have told Mr Nigel
Savage and Mr Marc Gordon - two managers of Govett Strategic Investment -
that he was comfortable with initial forecasts for Harland's pre-tax profits
of Pounds 13m to Pounds 14m.
The two fund managers bought 155,000 shares worth almost Pounds 1m in the
group just hours before the profits forecast was reduced to Pounds 4m and
the share price fell from 585p to 270p. The company eventually reported a
pre-tax loss of more than Pounds 6m.
Mr Ashman denies making a misleading statement contrary to section 47 of the
Financial Services Act 1986.
Mr Colin Nicholls QC, cross-examining, said the company had known by January
that year that the original profit forecast could not be met and that
something in the region of Pounds 6m was a more correct figure.
Mr Ashman replied: 'No one mentioned to me that the figure would be Pounds
6m.'
He denied saying anything to indicate Harland's profits would be in line
with the original forecasts. At the meeting with the two fund managers Mr
Savage had led the discussion and asked 'questions he should not have been
asking', Mr Ashman told the court.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
