<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Train franchise companies could get incentive payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES that win franchises to run train services could qualify for
incentive payments to meet punctuality and reliability targets, Roland Rudd
writes.
The scheme is included in draft objectives for the franchising director
which the government published yesterday. The director is Mr Roger Salmon, a
former director of the merchant bank NM Rothschild. He will be able to use
part of his budget on the incentives, which could be worth hundreds of
thousands of pounds.
Mr Salmon will be responsible for deciding who will run the franchises
created under the rail privatisation proposals, and will control subsidies
to lossmaking services.
Railtrack, which will be responsible for the running of the the track and
signalling, could also qualify for bonuses if it reduces costs.
Mr Salmon has been asked to outline a franchising programme by the end of
January. He will become responsible from April for paying subsidies, but
they will no longer be paid in an annual lump sum. Subsidy will be attached
to specific train operations, to prevent British Rail from cross-subsidising
bids for franchises.
When assessing bids from BR, Mr Salmon has been asked to take into account
its record in providing services and the transfer of risk. The government is
keen to transfer the financial risk associated with running a franchise from
the public to the private sector.
BR will only be able to bid for a franchise when there are no credible
alternatives from the private sector.
</TEXT>
