<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / World Trade News: Supersonic airliner gets new go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBAI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US government has given the go-ahead to the next stage of the programme
to build a supersonic airliner to replace Concorde.
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration will start work next year
on the second phase to develop the air frame, propulsion and systems
technologies over seven years at an expected cost of Dollars 1.2bn, Mr Lewis
Williams, Nasa's director of high speed research, said yesterday at an FT
conference at the Dubai Air Show.
Preliminary design studies have defined the characteristics of the aircraft,
planned to enter service early in the next century, which will have twice
Concorde's 3,000 nautical miles range and carry 300 passengers, three times
Concorde's capacity, at fare levels close to those charged on sub-sonic
aircraft.
Nasa began research in 1990, evaluating environmental considerations
including atmospheric effects, nitrogen oxide engine emissions, noise and
sonic boom. That first phase, costing about Dollars 400m, has shown the
aircraft to be 'environmentally compatible', said Mr Williams.
Although other government agencies, aircraft manufacturers and engine-makers
in other countries are collaborating on the supersonic aircraft study, the
US appears to be taking a far more active role in research. Nasa's annual
high speed research budget has just been increased from Dollars 117m this
year to Dollars 197m in 1994, although the agency had asked for Dollars 187m
for next year.
The US is keen to catch up with the European aerospace industry's expertise
and experience in supersonic airliner development through Concorde. However,
any future aircraft is expected to involve broad international co-operation
because it is widely accepted that the market will bear only one programme.
</TEXT>
