<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France's judicial authorities yesterday released almost all 88 people
rounded up by police in a vast search-and-arrest operation on Tuesday but
kept three for questioning, including two leaders of the Algerian Fraternity
in France, believed to be a front organisation for the Algerian Islamic
Front (FIS), Reuter reports from Paris. The Interior Ministry said
investigators found pro-FIS propaganda, false identity papers and money, but
no weapons. The government said the dragnet, a response to the abduction
last month of three French consular officials in Algiers, aimed to prevent
potential acts of violence.
