<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Paramount pays Dollars 552m for US publisher Macmillan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MACMILLAN, the largest US business in the empire of the late Mr Robert
Maxwell, was sold yesterday to Paramount Communications, which outbid rivals
with an offer of Dollars 552.75m (Pounds 366m).
Paramount owns publishing imprints such as Simon &amp; Schuster and Prentice
Hall. Its unsuccessful rivals in the final round of bidding are believed to
have been Harcourt Brace Jovanovich, the US educational publishers, K-111,
the US magazine company, and Pearson, the publishing and information group
that owns the Financial Times.
The sale agreement takes the gross total raised by administrators Price
Waterhouse from the sale of Maxwell Communication Corporation's US interests
beyond Dollars 1.5bn. Mr Mark Homan of Price Waterhouse said he believed the
net figure would fall within the predicted range of Dollars 700m-Dollars
1.1bn.
'We are looking pretty good on that,' Mr Homan said. He said he believed the
main Maxwell disposals in the US could be wrapped up by the year-end.
Offers are now being received for the last significant US business, Standard
Rate and Data, the specialist advertising industry publication.
The purchase of Macmillan will considerably strengthen the publishing
interests of Paramount, itself in Dollars 10bn merger talks with Viacom, the
US cable and television company.
Mr Martin Davis, chairman and chief executive of Paramount Communications,
said the transaction was 'a significant step in furthering our strategic
objective of creating proprietary intellectual properties that can be
distributed through a wide variety of media, from printed pages to computer
and video screens'.
As part of the sale, a reorganisation plan was filed under Chapter 11 in the
US Bankruptcy Court. Price Waterhouse said that was a technical step needed
'to remove the uncertainty created by Mr Maxwell's involvement with
Macmillan Inc'.
During a transition period, expected to last about three months, Mr Jonathan
Newcomb, president and chief operating officer, and Mr Andrew Evans, chief
finance officer of Paramount Publishing, will work on combining the two
companies.
Mr Richard Snyder, Paramount Publishing chairman, said the two businesses
were complementary and 'significant savings' were expected from integration.
Macmillan's backlist of authors includes Hemingway and Faulkner and its
publishing interests range from reference to children's books and general
fiction.
The prestige created by the Macmillan acquisition may expand possibilities
for Paramount's planned merger with Viacom, which is being hotly contested
by home shopping service QVC Network.
World stocks, Page 41
</TEXT>
