<HEADLINE>
FT  11 NOV 93 / Euro Disney hit by Pounds 610m loss: US parent under
pressure over rescue plan as leisure group's shares fall sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING and MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EURO DISNEY, the European leisure group controlled by Walt Disney of the US,
yesterday announced a net loss of FFr5.3bn (Pounds 610m) for the year to
September 30, prompting a sharp fall in the company's shares on
international stock markets.
The scale of the losses increases the urgency of a capital restructuring at
Euro Disney and puts pressure on Walt Disney, the US entertainment group, to
help rescue the leisure company.
Mr Philippe Bourguignon, Euro Disney's chairman, said the company would
require significant funding throughout the current financial year. He said
negotiations were under way with its banks and Walt Disney, and that he
hoped to complete a restructuring plan soon.
Industry observers said the fate of Euro Disney now rested largely in the
hands of Walt Disney, which holds 49 per cent of its shares. 'It is
make-your-mind-up time,' one analyst said.
Walt Disney said it would provide finance for Euro Disney for a limited
period to enable it to achieve a financial restructuring by spring 1994.
Euro Disney's losses included a write-off of FFr3.6bn for pre-opening costs
at the EuroDisneyland theme park in the eastern outskirts of Paris and for
planned redundancies.
The exceptional charges represent a serious blow to the company's capital
base, reducing shareholders' equity to just FFr1.5bn, compared with FFr7bn
at the end of September last year, using French accounting standards.
Euro Disney said it had written off all of its pre-opening costs, including
marketing and training expenses, to improve its future results.
The French theme park has been a growing worry for Walt Disney since it
opened 18 months ago. Bad weather has discouraged tourists who have
sometimes found it cheaper to go to Disney World in Florida.
Mr Bourguignon has taken a number of steps to encourage more visitors and to
entice them to part with their money. New rides have been opened, and prices
have been reduced sharply at the resort's hotels. Euro Disney reports some
success from its measures. Mr Bourguignon also points to the fact that 17m
visitors have come through the gates of EuroDisneyland in the first 18
months of its operation, making it, he says, Europe's largest tourist
attraction.
But even if visitors are being attracted, investors are still wary.
Yesterday, Euro Disney's shares fell sharply in London and Paris. In London,
shares fell by 72p to 436p after the results announcement. In Paris, shares
were temporarily suspended and fell by FFr5.7 to FFr38.
The bulk of the losses for the year to September 30 reflected the
exceptional charges relating to pre-opening costs and provisions for a
planned reduction in staff from 11,100 to just over 10,000. The net loss
before exceptional items was FFr1.7bn, which was achieved on revenues of
FFr5.7bn.
In view of the uncertainty surrounding Euro Disney, Walt Disney took a
Dollars 350m (Pounds 231.7m) charge against fourth-quarter earnings to
establish full reserves for the temporary funding and for receivables due
from the French associate.
Walt Disney's charge, together with its share of Euro Disney's operating
losses, meant the US company recorded a total Dollars 414.5m loss from the
European venture in the quarter and Dollars 514.7m in the full year.
That in turn pushed Walt Disney into a fourth quarter net loss of Dollars
77.8m, compared with net income of Dollars 223.7m in the same period of last
year. After heavy trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Walt Disney's
shares finished unchanged at Dollars 41 1/8.
Lex, Page 20
White-knuckle ride, Page 21
Walt Disney charge, Page 27
London stocks, Page 44
</TEXT>
