<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / EC system threatens trade figures' accuracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK is facing three years of unreliable and incomplete trade figures
because of difficulties with the European Community's new system of
measuring intra-community trade.
The Central Statistical Office said yesterday it was delaying publication of
complete visible-trade figures for the first eight months of this year
because lack of data had made it difficult seasonally to adjust the figures.
The delay marks a further setback for Intrastat, the EC's system based on
value added tax for measuring trade, which was introduced at the beginning
of the year to coincide with the single market.
Teething troubles with the system were expected to last until the middle of
this year. Statisticians now say that the latest difficulties may mean it is
three years before Britain has a reliable and complete series of statistics
on its trade with the rest of the world.
The CSO said that it needed another two days to 'reassess seasonal and
constant price adjustments made under the new system now in use throughout
the EC'.
It wants to make the next set of figures - the last before the Budget - as
accurate as possible to avoid large revisions after the chancellor has made
his statement.
The switch from a customs-based system of measuring intra-EC trade to one
based on VAT returns has been beset by problems since its introduction in
January. Last month, Eurostat, the EC's statistical office, said publication
of up-to-date figures was being hampered by a slow rate of reply by
companies, in particularly small companies.
The UK has been quicker to produce monthly figures than other member states,
although its plan to produce monthly figures by the end of July proved too
optimistic.
The latest setback comes as government officials from France, Germany, the
UK and the Netherlands meet in The Hague today to discuss difficulties with
Intrastat.
