<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Survey of Mexico (8): A thirst for expansion - Femsa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONTERREY began attracting money during the US civil war from the smuggling
of goods across the border to the Confederate states. Among the enterprises
built with the capital thus attracted to the city was a brewery, the
Cerveceria Cuauhtehmoc, which still stands today. It is now part of the
Femsa group, the headquarters of which abut on the brewery and which itself
is part of the Visa group.
The company began to shift its strategy from 1989, realising that thriving
in Mexico's newly-opened economy would require different qualities from
survival in a closed economy. Investments have been made, international
expansion is under way, and, say senior executives, the 'search continues
for other markets and other technologies'.
Femsa's beer brands are increasingly famous abroad: Dos Equis, Tecate, Carta
Blanca and Sol, to name a few. But Femsa - which employs 37,500 people and
had 1992 revenues of more than Dollars 2bn - is more than a beer company. It
has interests also in packaging, soft-drinks - it holds Mexico's Coca-Cola
franchise - and a chain of convenience stores.
This year, the company floated in the Mexican and international markets a
minority stake in its soft drinks subsidiary. Retaining a 51 per cent stake
for itself, it sold 30 per cent to Coca-Cola for Dollars 195m and 19 per
cent to the public for Dollars 177m.
The soft drinks subsidiary now plans to go after other markets, particularly
in Latin America and first perhaps in Argentina.
Mr Othon Ruiz, the company's chief executive, says the company is talking to
prospective foreign partners over similar arrangements in its packaging and
beer subsidiaries. Philip Morris of the US, maker of Miller beer and holder
of about 8 per cent of Femsa stock, is thought to be interested in the beer
business.
The company - forced to increase debt significantly after the acquisition by
Visa shareholders of Bancomer from the government - used the funds from the
flotation to pay down debt. Followers of the company say it remains fairly
heavily indebted and worry that some senior managers spend too much time on
the bank.
</TEXT>
