<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Survey of Mexico (6): Monterrey captures entrepreneurial
spirit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CITY of Monterrey in north-eastern Mexico, 200 kilometres from the
border with Texas, has long been known for its entrepreneurial spirit.
Sitting beneath the bone-dry mountains of the Sierra Madre, Monterrey - with
its freeways and fast food stores - often appears to have more in common
with the United States than with Mexico City.
Close though it is to the US, Monterrey cannot insulate itself from the
Mexican economy. Its companies are feeling the effects of slow growth which
has brought an end to the boom times in Mexico's third largest city, at
least for now. The companies face further challenges from the North American
Free Trade Agreement, if it comes about. If Monterrey's corporations cannot
handle the competition from the north, there seems little chance for most of
the rest of corporate Mexico.
The descendants of the founders of Monterrey's industrial base are still
prominent on the boards of the companies: members of the Garza family are
chairmen at Femsa and Alfa, the Sadas at Vitro and the Trevinos and
Zambranos elsewhere.
Their companies are often conglomerates - built up when Mexico's economy was
closed to the outside world and when expanding into other businesses was the
only wayto grow.
The opening of the Mexican economy has forced on many of them a different
business strategy. Many have shed peripheral businesses to concentrate on
one sector. Others still seem reluctant to sell or cede control of any
businesses, defying the conventional management wisdom that success stems
from specialisation. In the past few years, some of Monterrey's families
have diversified further particularly into the financial sector, buying
banks in privatisations.
Monterrey's companies are nonetheless probably better known outside Mexico
than ever.
Many are pushing into new markets; others are raising capital
internationally.
</TEXT>
<XX>
