<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / London Stock Exchange: Warburg gain reversed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE and PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RECENT boom in London's financial markets was underlined yesterday by a
surge in profits for SG Warburg. However, the reaction of investors
suggested that confidence in further rises in equity and bond markets may be
coming to an end.
One analyst said: 'All markets have gone their way, but this is a cyclical
business and Warburg will struggle to maintain momentum.' After hitting a
high of 890p in the morning, Warburg's share price closed 20 lower on the
day at 857p.
However, even the more pessimistic analysts were forced to upgrade forecasts
after Warburg announced first-half profits of Pounds 148.8m, against a
market consensus of Pounds 135m and a profit of Pounds 51.2m last time.
NatWest Securities, which had advised clients to take profits when
opportunities presented themselves, has shifted its full-year forecast to
Pounds 275m from Pounds 248m.
Among the more enthusiastic analysts, Mr Martin Green of Smith New Court
said he would be upgrading to above Pounds 300m, while Mr Martin Cross of
UBS also expected to be around Pounds 300m.
Mr Cross said that if first-half earnings were annualised, that would
indicate an undemanding p/e ratio of 11 times. He added that there were no
signs that the present economic conditions, which had done so much for
financial markets, were about to end.
</TEXT>
