<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIN prices collapsed on the London Metal Exchange yesterday afternoon when
the market broke below the Dollars 4,700 a tonne floor of the current
Dollars 200 technical range, dealers said. Sell stops pushed tin to a low of
Dollars 4,640 a tonne before some bargain-hunting trade buying emerged after
hours. Three-month tin closed Dollars 168 a tonne down at Dollars 4,649.50.
NICKEL capitalised on the recent improvement in sentiment, which has
resulted in less selling pressure when the market moves up. However, dealers
suggest the market remains oversupplied and is still in need of further
production cuts. Yesterday's advance petered out near the Dollars 4,800 a
tonne level once more and three-month prices finished at Dollars 4,757.50,
up Dollars 30. SILVER after a relatively strong performance on the New York
Commodity Exchange on Monday closed in London last night 40 cents up at
Dollars 4.525 an ounce. London SUGAR fell sharply yesterday afternoon in
hectic New York-led fund liquidation. Both white and raw sugar lost ground,
but by late afternoon in London the markets had steadied and prices
recovered.
Compiled from Reuters
