<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / International Company News: Viacom files fresh suit against
bid battle rival
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FOCUS of the Dollars 10bn takeover battle for Paramount Communications
shifted to legal ground yesterday as Viacom fired off a new anti-trust
complaint against rival bidder QVC Network. QVC independently said a key
challenge for it was winning a lawsuit against Viacom due to be heard next
week.
Viacom, which agreed to a friendly merger with Paramount in September, had
already filed a suit seeking to halt QVC's hostile offer, on the grounds
that it was part of a monopolistic conspiracy by Tele-Communications (TCI),
the cable television group.
Since Viacom filed that suit, TCI has announced a plan to acquire associated
cable programme company, Liberty Media, and itself be acquired by Bell
Atlantic, the telephone company. Liberty Media owns 22 per cent of QVC.
Viacom yesterday amended its suit to include the Bell Atlantic-TCI-Liberty
merger in its complaint, and said the TCI-Liberty-QVC bid for Paramount had
caused it 'enormous damage'. It also named Comcast, a cable company which
owns 22 per cent of QVC, as an additional defendant.
Separately, the Federal Trade Commission, which examines anti-trust issues,
is thought to be near a decision on what, if any, stake Liberty Media can
have in QVC if the company wins its bid for Paramount.
</TEXT>
