<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / International Company News: Motorola and Nextel in Dollars
1.8bn mobile radio deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEXTEL, a rapidly expanding US mobile data communications services company,
plans to construct a nationwide advanced digital communications network that
will compete with existing cellular telephone services.
Nextel is buying licences to operate mobile communications services in
several of the largest metropolitan areas in the US from Motorola, the
makers of semiconductors and communications systems, in a deal worth about
Dollars 1.8bn.
Nextel has purchased licences from Motorola covering the use of more than
2,500 radio frequencies in 21 states. These specialised mobile radio
services are used for dispatch of taxis and other vehicle fleets.
In exchange for its radio frequency licenses, Motorola will receive a 20 per
cent stake in Nextel and is providing Dollars 260m in new financing. These
arrangements will result in more than Dollars 500m in financing being
provided by Motorola, Nextel said.
Nextel announced that it had reached a technology alliance with Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone of Japan. NTT has taken an equity stake in Nextel,
purchasing 1.5m shares for Dollars 75m. NTT will assist Nextel in developing
its digital wireless network.
When fully constructed in 1995, Nextel's networks would be capable of
reaching 180m people across the US, the company said. Services will include
mobile telephone, dispatch, alpha-numeric paging and data transmission from
a single mobile telephone handset.
'We view this transaction with Motorola as the capstone of our acquisition
campaign,' said Mr Morgan O'Brien, chairman of Nextel. In recent weeks
Nextel, formerly called Fleet Call, has spent more than Dollars 1bn to
acquire dispatch service licenses in various parts of the US.
Nextel's goal is to upgrade these systems with digital technology developed
by Motorola, which will provide the company with equipment and technical
assistance.
'In the six years of our existence, we have completed 125 transactions,
acquired thousands of frequencies in hundreds of markets and raised more
than Dollars 1.2bn in financing. Now we can turn our full attention to
deploying the nation's first network of all-digital, integrated wireless
communications,' said Mr O'Brien.
Nextel has started offering its integrated digital services in southern
California. The company said its services would cover most of the state
within the first quarter of 1994. New services will be available in New York
and Chicago by mid-1994. For Motorola, the biggest operator of dispatch
services in the US, the sale reflects its decision to offer technology and
equipment rather than provide services.
Motorola recently sold 42 per cent of its dispatch service licences to
CenCall and Dial Page, both dispatch service providers, in exchange for
stock valued at about Dollars 1.2bn.
</TEXT>
