<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If your father had been a Nazi war criminal would you agree to go to Israel
to discuss the subject with the children of holocaust survivors? Some did
and Timewatch was there to record the confrontation (BBC2, 8.00).
ITV also offers a heavyweight subject in its two-hour drama documentary
Fighting For Gemma (8.00). Gemma D'Arcy, whose father worked at the nuclear
plant in Sellafield, developed leukaemia, and solicitor Martyn Day became
convinced there was a causal link between the plant and a high incidence of
blood cancer.
Provided the other parts of The Buddha Of Suburbia are as funny and telling
as the opening episode, BBC2 will have brought us something far better than
'My Beautiful Laundrette' , also written by Hanif Kureishi. This tells you
more about the experience of being regarded as an alien, though born in
Bromley, than half a dozen 'race' series (9.25).
Political history will surely never be the same again after Thatcher: The
Downing Street Years, which ends this evening with Lady T. giving her
version of her departure from office (BBC1, 9.30).
</TEXT>
