<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Jobs and prices warning over VAT on food
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BIG job losses and price rises in many consumer products would result if
value added tax were extended to all food and drink, the industry warned
yesterday.
The Food and Drink Federation, which represents manufacturers, said that if
VAT were applied at the standard 17.5 per cent rate to the 80 per cent of
food and drink products now zero-rated, retail prices would rise by more
than 2 per cent and 31,000 manufacturing jobs would go. Its members would
suffer a 0.9 percentage-point drop in their average profit margins, and
retailers' profitability would be depressed.
The federation's warning is part of its campaign to persuade Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, not to extend VAT in the Budget. If VAT were
extended to all food and drink at an 8 per cent rate, 8,000 jobs would be
lost and profit margins would be reduced by 0.8 percentage points, the
federation said.
It added that estimates by accountants Price Waterhouse showed that, in the
event of a 17.5 per cent extension, about 40 per cent of the higher costs
due to a change in VAT treatment would feed through into higher prices, and
the remainder would be absorbed by manufacturers and retailers.
Half the impact on manufacturers would be absorbed by shedding jobs, one
third through gains in general efficiency and 17 per cent in a 0.9
percentage-point fall in average profit margins.
About 380,000 people are employed in food manufacturing.
Tax incentives for investment in training and manufacturing are among the
measures businesses in north-east England most want to see in the Budget,
says a Price Waterhouse survey.
</TEXT>
