<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Car sales rise of 4% forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK NEW CAR sales are expected to rise by 4 per cent to 5 per cent next year,
the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders said yesterday. This would
mean a 1994 total of 1.85m, after an increase of more than 11 per cent this
year to between 1.77m and 1.78m.
Motor industry leaders warned, however, that the economic recovery remained
fragile and needed 'nurturing'. They expressed concern that any significant
increase in taxation in the Budget later this month would halt the recovery
in its tracks.
'The last thing we need as an industry or as an economy is a greater tax
burden,' said Mr Geoffrey Whalen, SMMT president and managing director of
Peugeot Talbot.
In spite of the rise in domestic demand, most carmakers in the UK had been
forced to cut production because of the steep fall in new car sales in
mainland Europe. The drop in west European car demand had caused 100,000
cars to be lost from UK production schedules, Mr Whalen said.
UK car output was still expected to rise to 1.35m this year - its highest
level since the mid-1970s - from 1.29m in 1992, mainly because of the
substantial capacity added by the Japanese carmakers Nissan, Toyota and
Honda.
Output next year was expected to reach about 1.45m.
Marketing campaigns are also expected to increase in intensity. 'With the
markets in continental Europe still suffering, manufacturers across the
Channel are switching their attention to Britain in an effort to keep up
their own production,' the SMMT said.
</TEXT>
