<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Tory concern at lone-parent plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BACKBENCH Tory MPs yesterday expressed concern over the suggestion in a
leaked document that the government should cut social security benefits to
single parents.
The proposal, discussed recently by a cabinet committee, caused a storm in
Whitehall yesterday after the leak of the discussion document on ways to
tackle 'the burden on public expenditure caused by lone parent families'.
The document, written by senior Whitehall officials, outlined possible lines
of action to reduce the number of single parent families, most of which are
headed by women. They included reducing social security benefit, increasing
emphasis on sex education and transferring some financial responsibility for
the children to their grandparents.
Another suggestion was that the age of consent be reduced from 16 to 13, so
that GPs could prescribe contraceptives.
It emerged yesterday that the document had been discussed by EDH, the
cabinet committee on home and social affairs. The meeting, chaired by Lord
Wakeham, the Lord Privy Seal, probably took place on September 21 and was
attended by Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary.
A discussion at this level suggests that the government is close to making
formal proposals to parliament. An official said the committee had rejected
the idea of reducing the age of consent as 'nonsense'.
Mr Lilley yesterday tried to defuse the row over the document, claiming that
his first concern was to look after the interests of the children concerned.
But he admitted that the government was looking at ways to cut some of the
costs of supporting this social group. 'We believe that people should
support each other, particularly that parents should support their children.
The taxpayer should only become involved when they don't have the money to
do so.'
Some Conservative backbenchers said they would resist any proposal to cut
benefit for lone parents. Mr David Shaw, MP for Dover and a member of the
Commons Social Security Committee, said that this would hurt the children of
the parent.
Ms Teresa Gorman, Conservative MP for Billericay, and Mrs Emma Nicholson
(Devon West) also criticised the targetting of single women for benefit
cuts. 'It ill-behoves men to make these judgments on single women,' said Ms
Gorman. 'Most of us - but for the grace of God - might have found ourselves
in their position.'
</TEXT>
