<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Director is jailed for five years: Pounds 2.1m tax fraud
conducted through 'phoenix' companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMPANY director was yesterday jailed for five years for his part in a
Pounds 2.1m tax fraud through 'phoenix' companies. The sentence is believed
to be the most severe custodial penalty yet imposed for contrived
liquidations.
The 3 1/2 -year investigation spanned more than 16 companies in four linked
phoenix operations. The prosecution said the liquidations, involving a
number of City and West End employment agencies, were contrived to avoid
tax.
The case follows calls by the Confederation of British Industry for reform
of insolvency legislation to prevent 'reckless' directors from leaving
behind a 'trail of debt' while continuing to trade in phoenix companies. It
also prompted warnings by Customs and Excise that the use of phoenix
companies is increasing.
Phoenix companies are businesses which fold only to rise again, often under
a slightly different name in the hands of the same directors and management.
Debts, usually unpaid tax, are left in the original company, leaving
creditors to claim from an empty shell.
The new company often buys the stock of the first company at big discounts
and continues to trade with its customers who may not know they are dealing
with a new company.
In addition to the jail sentence, Mr Christopher Tarpey, of Swiss Cottage,
north London, was disqualified from being a company director for 12 years.
He was ordered to pay the tax authorities Pounds 106,000 in compensation. A
Middlesex Crown Court jury had found him guilty on eight counts of cheating
the Inland Revenue under common law.
Two other men, Mr Kevin Nolan and Mr Paul Cressey, also from the London
area, both of whom pleaded guilty, were also jailed for 18 and 15 months
respectively.
They were both barred from being company directors for five years.
One of the agencies, Sandhurst Recruitment Services (SRS), traded as Legal
Staff. It was set up in September 1985 and liquidated in October 1989, with
Crown debts of Pounds 270,862.
A second company, this time registered as Legal Staff, was set up in April
1988, and took over the business of SRS. It also traded as Legal Staff from
the same London address. It was liquidated in November 1990 owing Pounds
191,244 in tax.
A third company, Dulagood, set up in November 1990, also traded as Legal
Staff from the same address but did not accrue a tax debt because the
principals were arrested in December of that year.
Customs and Excise said the prosecution, which it led with support of the
Inland Revenue, is the most recent evidence of an increase in contrived
liquidations.
It said: 'Phoenixism is on the increase and has been on the increase for a
number of years now. The amount of Crown taxes lost by this means of fraud
is of great concern to the revenue departments.' The sum ran into millions,
Customs added.
The CBI said yesterday: 'CBI members report a regular incidence of phoenix
companies. Experience has clearly shown that current legislation is not
effective and does not appear to be enforced.'
The Department of Trade and Industry yesterday published proposals to reform
aspects of company insolvency law, but they do not affect contrived
liquidations. It said it believed the present law was adequate although all
legislation was constantly under review.
</TEXT>
<XX>
