<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Call for longer university years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONGER academic years and a move away from the honours degree system were
urged by the Royal Society yesterday as part of a package of reforms for
higher education.
But the society ruled out making graduates pay for their tuition, a measure
which has been proposed by several university vice-chancellors in the last
few months. Instead, it suggested the state should also pay tuition fees in
full for part-time students but that student maintenance costs should be
funded by a graduate tax.
The Committee of Vice-chancellors and Principals welcomed the proposals.
Among the society's other proposals were:
Some universities should concentrate on teaching and move towards a longer
academic year.
Honours classification should be replaced with a detailed account of
assessment throughout the course.
Qualifications such as certificates and diplomas of higher education should
be introduced, to be finished in less than three years.
New modular courses, allowing students to move from university, or to shift
between work and education.
Higher Education Futures, Publication Sales Department, The Royal Society, 6
Carlton House Terrace, London SW1Y 5AG. Pounds 15.50.
</TEXT>
