<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Whitehall fights a war of words: A look at the Ministry of
Defence's campaign to stave off cuts in its budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AIR CHIEF Marshal Sir Michael Graydon, chief of the air staff, is not a man
given to dramatic public statements. So when he accuses the Treasury of
running a 'disreputable' campaign to discredit the services, Westminster
sits up and takes notice.
Addressing the Air League on Monday, Sir Michael accused the Treasury of
portraying the military as 'fat, inefficient and poorly organised' in order
to lay the groundwork for swingeing defence cuts in the Budget.
Sir Michael named no names, and he apologised yesterday - after pressure
from the Ministry of Defence - for any embarrassment he may have caused
ministers.
But his outburst raises a series of questions about the role of the
Treasury, the service chiefs and their political masters at the defence
ministry in the Budget debate.
Defence sources pointed the finger of blame squarely at Mr Michael Portillo,
the steadfastly rightwing chief secretary to the Treasury, who has argued
strongly for public spending restraint.
Mr Portillo last night denied any involvement in Treasury leaks. But
officials were pointing out that there was nothing unusual about this year's
public spending round, which followed much the same course of leak and
counter-leak as those of previous years.
If battle was joined with greater verve than is usual, it was because the
defence budget is one of the few big areas which could be cut to keep public
spending within the agreed control total of Pounds 254bn.
In the event, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, fought off demands
for cuts of up to Pounds 1bn this year, and settled for a reduction in the
defence budget of Pounds 1.3bn over three years.
The agreement was preceded by a great deal of horsetrading, during which the
Treasury drew journalists' attention to various military inefficiencies
which could be exploited to yield savings.
These ranged from the comic to the dramatic. One minister, for example,
suggested that worthwhile savings could be achieved if the services gave up
their separate facilities for making false teeth.
The defence chiefs seem to have been most upset by suggestions that there
were too many senior officers - particularly in the navy, said to have more
than 40 admirals who never go to sea.
But while the Treasury was quick to exploit some of these suggestions in its
campaign for spending cuts, the defence chiefs are making a mistake in
identifying Mr Portillo, or his civil servants, as sources.
The story that most angered the service chiefs - the revelation that lower
ranks had borne the brunt of reductions in staffing since 1970 - was based
on freely available information published by the defence ministry.
Much of the other material which upset the forces came from a cabinet
minister from another department who has thought deeply about defence issues
but has no contact with the Treasury.
In short, there was no organised Treasury campaign to undermine the defence
forces. But there was a behind-the-scenes campaign by the defence department
to mobilise backbench Conservative opinion against the proposed cuts.
That campaign, which culminated in a threatened rebellion by Tory MPs, was
clearly assisted by a much-publicised visit by Sir Michael and the other
defence chiefs to complain about the potential impact of cuts in spending.
</TEXT>
