<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Airlines face 60% rise in insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL airlines are facing increases of about 60 per cent in the cost
of insurance cover.
The rises follow several years of weak trading performance by aviation
insurers, with claims from accidents and other losses regularly exceeding
premiums - a trend highlighted by a possible claim for more than Dollars
100m (Pounds 66m) after a China Airlines Boeing 747 plunged into Hong Kong
harbour last week.
The rises should signal improving prospects of profitability for
underwriters at Lloyd's of London, a leading market for aviation insurance.
'Underwriters have lost money for a number of years,' said Mr Matthew Day,
of Willis Corroon Aerospace, a leading buyer of airline insurance.
Three out of four airlines renew covers in the last quarter of each year.
Rates vary according to the claims record of each airline during the past 12
months. But according to figures published by Willis Corroon, many airlines
that renewed their policies on October 1 paid steep increases.
Increases ranged from 147 per cent for hull cover and 110 per cent for its
liability risks paid by one Asian airline to 31 per cent for hull and 54 per
cent for liabilities for a smaller European airline.
Premiums for hulls range from 0.14 per cent to 0.6 per cent of value and
liability premiums range from 0.2 per cent to 1 per cent of 'revenue
passenger kilometres', a measure of the airline's passenger traffic used by
insurers.
After the increases, total premiums for 1993 are expected to be Dollars
898m, said Willis, against Dollars 579m in the same period of 1992. Large
claims have so far cost insurers about Dollars 300m (a figure which is
understood to exclude the recent Hong Kong crash) although the market has
also been hit by a large number of partial and 'attritional' losses (when
aircraft are damaged, not destroyed).
As part of the trend towards a tighter market, insurers have also pressed
airlines to accept higher deductibles (the amount paid by the insurance
buyer).
The ability of underwriters to impose increases reflects the withdrawal from
the market of a number of insurers, including syndicates at Lloyd's, earlier
this year.
</TEXT>
