<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Birmingham's budget attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BIRMINGHAM City Council has been told by its own advisers to shift its
spending priorities from the provision of international facilities, such as
its convention centre, to a crash programme on improving education.
The Birmingham Education Commission, set up by the council to advise on
future educational needs in England's biggest local authority, said
yesterday: 'Birmingham can be proud of its international facilities. But the
state of its school buildings brings shame to the city.'
Since fiscal 1989-90, the city council has spent Pounds 236m less on
education than the government, in its standard spending assessment, assumed
it would. This period covered the opening of the convention centre, indoor
sports arena and an extension to the National Exhibition Centre.
The commission is suggesting the council should spend Pounds 300m more than
its standard spending assessment figure over the next five years.
The council yesterday welcomed the report and Ms Theresa Stewart, the Labour
leader, promised that school repairs would be 'a priority in our budget
planning process'.
Britain's economic performance lags behind that of its European competitors
because of insufficient craft training, says a paper published by the
National Institute of Economic and Social Research, John Authers writes.
Professor Sig Prais, of the institute, says 64 per cent of Britain's
workforce has no vocational qualifications. In Germany this figure is only
26 per cent, and in Switzerland 23 per cent. Britain's deficiency is most
marked in 'intermediate' craft qualifications, at the level of City and
Guilds Part One and above, and BTec national diplomas.
