<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / CBI urges wide reform of Tecs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry yesterday criticised the government
for being too prescriptive in the detailed running of Training and
Enterprise Councils, while failing to give them strategic leadership.
The CBI's criticisms are contained in a policy document on employer-led
Tecs, which administer government-funded training programmes in England and
Wales. The criticisms will be discussed at the CBI's annual conference in
Harrogate next week.
The report expressed broad support for Tecs, which spend Pounds 2bn of
public funds, but highlighted up to 50 areas where the CBI believed there
was need for reform.
Proposals directed at the government, Tecs and in some instances Local
Enterprise Companies included:
A thorough review of the contracts between the government and Tecs, and a
parallel exercise to simplify the administrative requirements Tecs imposed
on suppliers.
Funding of Tecs through an intermediary council, rather than directly by the
department of employment.
A clearer government statement of the role of Tecs.
More local accountability, with codes of best practice to ensure greater
local involvement.
The report also gave an implicit warning to the government that it should
not strip Tecs of their responsibility for Youth Training. The Department
for Education has sought to transfer more than half of Youth Training's
budget to its further education colleges.
The CBI said the government's new emphasis on Tecs' enterprise role should
'not be interpreted as making training a secondary priority, but should
require a new balance to be struck'.
</TEXT>
