<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / World Trade News: British Telecom to invest in satellite
services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBAI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH TELECOM is investing about Dollars 200m (Pounds 132m) in financing
new satellite telecommunication equipment on board commercial airliners to
position itself in the emerging market for aircraft satellite communication
services.
The BT investment reflects the growing interest of international
telecommunication companies in new airline satellite communication systems
which, together with new satellite navigation systems, are expected to
revolutionise commercial air transport over the next 20 years.
'The introduction of new satellite navigation and communication technology
is expected to be as significant for the airline industry as the transition
from the turbo-propellor aircraft to the jet in the 1950s,' Mr William
Fromme, director of the air navigation bureau of the International Civil
Aviation Organisation (ICAO), the aviation arm of the United Nations, said
yesterday at a Financial Times conference at the Dubai Air Show.
Mr Fromme said new satellite telecommunication and navigation systems were
expected to improve sharply safety and airspace management and provide
significant economic advantages to airlines. But according to the
International Air Transport Association (Iata) studies one of the biggest
pay-offs would for telecommunication companies because of the increased use
of satellite telecommunications on board aircraft.
Apart from BT, the US Comsat satellite telecommunication group and Teleglobe
of Canada are already committed to substantial investment of airborne
telecommunication technology and equipment.
So far, about 300 aircraft have been equipped with satellite communication
packages. The cost of installing this equipment on board is about Dollars
500,000 per aircraft.
With many financially strapped airlines reluctant to financethis new
communication equipment, telecommunication companies appear increasingly
interested because of the expectation of long-term revenue flows.
'Up to now, many people appear to have underestimated the potential revenues
from on-board personal services like communications, information and
entertainment,' Mr Fromme said. Studies have suggested that airline
passengers could spend between Dollars 20 to Dollars 40 a year each on
onboard communication services.
Emirates, the Dubai-based airline, estimates that passengers could spend up
to Dollars 100 a year each on on-board electronic shopping facilities.
Mr Richard Branson's Virgin Atlantic Airways also sees onboard electronic
shopping and entertainment as providing an increasing source of revenue for
airlines to offset continued pressure on fares.
</TEXT>
