<HEADLINE>
FT  10 NOV 93 / Mirror in move to end rift with press watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DEAL that could end the crisis over the Princess of Wales pictures and
pave the way for Mirror Group Newspapers to return to the Press Complaints
Commission appeared to be taking shape last night.
Lawyers acting for MGN met commission officials as senior figures in the
newspaper industry tried to prevent the breakdown of press self-regulation
and the imposition of statutory controls.
Mr David Montgomery, chief executive of MGN, has made it clear he will enter
into negotiations on returning to the regulatory body if Lord McGregor of
Durris, commission chairman, withdraws remarks criticising the Daily Mirror
and advocating a readers' and advertisers' boycott.
Three MGN titles quit the press watchdog on Monday after Mr Montgomery
accused Lord McGregor of exceeding his powers and behaving unfairly. MGN is
angry that Lord McGregor appears to have prejudged any possible complaints
on the Mirror's use of pictures of the Princess exercising at a gym.
It is believed that senior figures such as Mr Rupert Murdoch, chairman of
News Corporation, and Sir David English, chairman of Associated Newspapers,
have given informal undertakings that attacks on the Daily Mirror by their
publications will cease.
Last night a spokesman for the Mirror said other newspapers had promised to
end the 'dog eat dog' criticism of its use of the pictures. In today's
edition an editorial says the 'abusive campaign' had pilloried the paper
before any hearing.
Lawyers for the Princess of Wales yesterday issued two writs, against MGN
and the L A Fitness Club, where the unauthorised pictures were taken. The
writs made it clear the Princess wanted the illicit pictures and negatives.
Mr Montgomery was advised by at least one senior newspaper executive that
MGN should apologise to the Princess and make a payment to charity.
MGN has received undertakings that controversial remarks by the press
watchdog will not be repeated. Lawyers Theodore Goddard wrote to Lord
McGregor arguing that 'it is not, as I am sure you will accept, the role of
the commission and its chairman to call for penalties to be imposed on a
newspaper in circumstances where no proper or indeed any inquiry has been
made into the case'. The lawyers added that Lord McGregor had exceeded his
powers in urging a boycott.
The regulatory body will meet today as planned, but will not discuss the
pictures because the matter is 'sub-judice', Lord McGregor said last night.
</TEXT>
