<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Further fall in inflation rate of goods leaving factories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RATE of inflation for goods leaving factories fell for the second
consecutive month in October, indicating that price pressures in the economy
remain subdued as manufacturers hold down prices.
Output prices rose 0.2 per cent in October to stand 4 per cent up on a year
ago. This compares with 4.2 per cent in September and 4.3 per cent in
August, and prompted some economists to suggest that producer output
inflation has passed its peak.
But the underlying measure rose for the sixth successive month. This index,
which excludes volatile prices of food, drink, tobacco and petrol, rose 3.2
per cent in the 12 months to October, compared with 3 per cent in the 12
months to September. It has risen every month since April, when the annual
rate was 2.2 per cent.
The Central Statistical Office said the seasonally adjusted rise in the
underlying index in the latest three months was equivalent to an annual rate
of increase of 3.6 per cent.
There was a sharp fall in input-price inflation. Prices of industry's raw
materials and fuel rose 0.9 per cent in the 12 months to October compared
with 3.8 per cent in September. The steep fall was mainly due to the
year-on-year comparison.
</TEXT>
