<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / US attack on Tokyo over trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US increased pressure on Japan yesterday to bring down its trade
surplus, urging Tokyo to cut income taxes substantially so that consumers
have more money to spend on imports, Reuter reports from Washington.
Administration officials repeatedly hammered Japan for failing to do more to
spur growth and open its markets to imports. Nearly half of the annual US
trade deficit is with Japan.
'I am concerned that Japanese growth appears to be slowing and Japanese
demand for foreign products is increasing less rapidly than had been hoped,'
Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bensten said in a statement.
US officials pin hopes on reform of Japan's tax system. A Japanese advisory
panel is expected to issue a report on tax reform in mid-November.
Deputy Treasury Secretary Roger Altman told a Senate finance sub-committee:
'Strong fiscal action through a stimulative tax programme could be the key
to reviving growth.'
