<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / US foreign policy official resigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Clifton Wharton last night said he was resigning as deputy secretary of
state, the first change in the US foreign policy team since President Bill
Clinton took office.
Mr Wharton, a former university president and head of the largest
educational pension fund, held extensive weekend talks with Mr Warren
Christopher, the secretary of state. Announcing his decision last night, Mr
Wharton said in a written statement: 'In the past two weeks it became
unmistakeably clear that I was being subjected to the classic Washington
practice of sustained anonymous leaks to the media.'
The son of the first black American ever to attain ambassadorial rank, Mr
Wharton was mostly engaged in administrative affairs, including the
reorganisation of US foreign aid programmes.
But with the administration's conduct of foreign policy under fire on
several fronts, Mr Christopher has reportedly been pressing for a stronger
team, with elevation of an articulate and possibly experienced diplomat to
serve as deputy believed on his agenda.
The foreign policy triumvirate of Mr Christopher, Mr Anthony Lake, national
security adviser, and Mr Les Aspin, defence secretary, have all been subject
to direct criticism. The secretary of state himself, according to the New
York Times, has even suggested recruiting someone along the lines of Mr
David Gergen, counsellor to the president, to ensure foreign policy
dissemination is co-ordinated properly.
Several internal candidates exist. They include Mr Thomas Pickering,
currently ambassador to Russia, Mr Strobe Talbott, who has proved
particularly effective as ambassador-at-large for the former Soviet states,
and Mr Winston Lord, the mandarin now serving as undersecretary for Asian
affairs. Outsiders from the extensive Washington foreign policy
establishment also cannot be excluded.
</TEXT>
