<HEADLINE>
FT  09 NOV 93 / Croats angered by Vitez attack
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOSLEM forces yesterday fired two shells on a Croat-held munitions factory
in Vitez, central Bosnia, as Croat officials warned the attacks could prompt
'a catastrophe'.
Faced with a string of Moslem victories, the Croat authorities said the
latest Moslem offensive would cause 'a horrific explosion and an
unprecedented catastrophe for the wider area of Bosnia-Hercegovina'.
It was said to be the first direct hit on the vital munitions factory in
Vitez, the headquarters of British United Nations soldiers, and follows the
fall last week of Vares, 25 miles to the east, to the Moslem government's
forces.
The Croatian Defense Council (HVO), the Bosnian Croat army, admitted in a
statement it had joined forces with the Bosnian Serbs, their former enemies,
to surround the Nordic UN battalion near Vares on Sunday.
The two-hour encirclement helped the Croats retake several villages, which
the HVO statement cited as proof of UN support for Moslem forces, Belgrade
radio reported.
In Sarajevo, UN soldiers yesterday escorted the first of 1,500 Serbs, Croats
and Moslems to be evacuated from the besieged Bosnian capital as part of an
agreement postponed for nearly one year.
Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg, the UN envoy, is due to meet Mr Alija Izetbegovic,
the Bosnian president, in Sarajevo today to consider possible steps to
revive the peace talks.
Meanwhile, Sarajevo radio said Serb forces pounded the Moslem enclave of
Gorazde, a UN-designated 'safe area' in south-eastern Bosnia.
</TEXT>
